p-value is 2.2e-16 which is below 0.05. So the corelationship between temperature and ozone is significant. When ozone increase 1 unit, temperature increases 0.20081 unit. When ozone is zero, temperature is estimated to be 69.41072.

plot(Temp ~ Ozone, data = airquality)
abline(lm(Temp ~ Ozone, data = airquality), col = "red")

Exercise 4 (R code and outputs required)

1

Remember that SSY is comprised of both SSYp (SSY) and SSE. Please calculate SSE. I know this may be hard, but you can do it! Then, verify that SSY - SSYp is equal to SSE. What is SSE measuring in non-technical terms?

mod <- lm(Temp ~ Wind, data = airquality)
summary(mod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Temp ~ Wind, data = airquality)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -23.291  -5.723   1.709   6.016  19.199 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  90.1349     2.0522  43.921  < 2e-16 ***
## Wind         -1.2305     0.1944  -6.331 2.64e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 8.442 on 151 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2098, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2045 
## F-statistic: 40.08 on 1 and 151 DF,  p-value: 2.642e-09
r2 <- summary(mod)$r.squared
y <- airquality$Temp
meany <- mean(y)
diff <- y - meany
SSY <- sum(diff^2)
x <- data.frame(Wind = airquality$Wind)
predy <- predict.lm(mod,x)
meany <- mean(y)
diff <- predy - meany
SSYp <- sum(diff^2)
diff <- y - predy
SSE <- sum(diff^2)
SSE
## [1] 10761.49
SSE <- SSY - SSYp
SSE
## [1] 10761.49

SSE(error sum of squares) measures the square of difference in y and predicted y which is the part can not be explained by the variation of the predicted variable.

Exercise 5 (R code and outputs required)

1

Create a linear model using the airquality dataset with Temp as your dependent variable and Ozone as your independent variable. Check and comment on whether your model meets the assumptions of homoscedasticity and normality using the plots and tests we used above.

homoscedasticity

mod <- lm(Temp ~ Ozone, data = airquality)
summary(mod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Temp ~ Ozone, data = airquality)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -22.147  -4.858   1.828   4.342  12.328 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 69.41072    1.02971   67.41   <2e-16 ***
## Ozone        0.20081    0.01928   10.42   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 6.819 on 114 degrees of freedom
##   (37 observations deleted due to missingness)
## Multiple R-squared:  0.4877, Adjusted R-squared:  0.4832 
## F-statistic: 108.5 on 1 and 114 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
plot(Temp ~ Ozone, data = airquality)

#install.packages('lmtest')
#install.packages('car')
library(lmtest)
## Loading required package: zoo
## 
## Attaching package: 'zoo'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     as.Date, as.Date.numeric
library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
bptest(mod)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  mod
## BP = 3.2346, df = 1, p-value = 0.0721
ncvTest(mod)
## Non-constant Variance Score Test 
## Variance formula: ~ fitted.values 
## Chisquare = 3.266367, Df = 1, p = 0.070714

In Breusch-Pagan test, p-value = 0.0721. P -value is greater than 0.05. In the Non-constant Variance Score Test, p=0.070714. Both of these results show that our p-value is > 0.05, therefore we fail to reject the null hypothesis of homoscedasticity, and our residuals are homoscedastic.

normality

qqPlot(residuals(mod),id=FALSE)

shapiro.test(residuals(mod))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  residuals(mod)
## W = 0.94867, p-value = 0.000226

Part of residuals fall within the dotted blue lines, and p-value is below 0.05. So the null hypothsis that errors are normally distributed is rejected. Errors are not normally distributed.
